In the wilderness, he fasted. He wept for justice. And he prayedâ€”not to the many gods of empire, but to the One he felt but had not yet named. He said:

â€œO invisible Lord, if you dwell in the sky or in the air, know that I seek you not for conquest, but for clarity. Show me the path of wisdom, not just of power.â€

â€”

He wandered in exile for years, learning the language of birds, the silence of mountains, and the secrets of men. He studied engineering and philosophy among allies, storing knowledge like seed for a future spring. When he was grown, the flame within him had not dimmed. With wisdom and courage, he returned to his homeland and joined the Mexica and Tlacopan in a sacred alliance.

Through battle, diplomacy, and righteous vision, he reclaimed Texcocoâ€”not with vengeance, but with justice. And when he was crowned king, he did not glorify himself with gold or blood. Instead, he raised schools, aqueducts, gardens, and courts of law. He said:

â€œWhat is the worth of a king who builds palaces but forgets the voice of the poor?â€

â€”

