â€œO Lord of the Near and the Close, the Giver of Life, you who dwell in the mist beyond the sunâ€”are you pleased by the hearts of men, or by their kindness?â€

And in the silence, he felt peace. Not thunder, not omenâ€”but the presence of the One. From that day, he prayed not to the many gods, but to Tloque Nahuaque, the God unknown to idolsâ€”the One God, invisible, eternal, beyond form but present in truth.

â€”

He began to teach that God could not be captured in stone, nor satisfied by blood. He outlawed human sacrifice in Texcoco and replaced fear with law. He built a temple not to a figure, but to the skyâ€”open to wind and light, with no idols, only space for the soul to meet its Maker.

